					<p><em>Haiti, Untitled</em> (1996) by Jørgen Leth depicts in an intriguing way a country caught in political upheaval, and the ensuing chaos of the first half of the 1990s. By employing a non-linear narrative and through his use of a very specific editing technique, Leth constructs a heteroglossic “thick film” (this term is not to be equated with Clifford Geertz’s “thick description”). Leth’s work may, however, stir some controversy due to the author’s take on exoticization and nostalgia. These issues, among others, are discussed in the paper.</p>
