				<div class="c-issue-toc__article-collapse-inner">
					<p>Starting from the theatrical poster for a play based on Raymond Roussel’s <em>Impressions d'Afrique</em>, the author attempts to interpret it in the light of Roussel’s literary experiments and colonial stereotypes from the beginning of the 20th century. The poster resonates in two different, complementary contexts that undermine its unequivocal character and question its realism. Roussel’s novel and stage piece (as well as the poster) ironically plays with the colonial tradition and reveals its deconstructive potential.</p>
